  A3. Coldreach — Signal-Based Selling
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  HIGH-LEVEL CONCEPT:
  Instead of monitoring "intent" (what people read), Coldreach monitors "events" (what
  companies DO — hire, post, raise money, announce projects). You define buying signals
  in plain English, and it watches for them. Every outreach message anchored to a verified
  buying signal.

  IMPLEMENTATION DETAIL:

  Signal definition (the core differentiator):
  - Plain English input: "Company just raised Series B and is hiring VP of Sales"
  - Or: "Company posted a job mentioning Salesforce migration"
  - Or: "CEO posted on LinkedIn about struggling with outbound"
  - LLM (likely GPT-4 class) interprets the definition and converts to monitoring query
  - UI shows: text input field, example templates, preview of matched accounts before
    activating
  - This is genuinely novel — competitors require pre-defined signal categories or
    technical configuration
  Evidence: https://www.producthunt.com/posts/coldreach, https://www.coldreach.ai/

  How signals are detected:
  - Data sources scanned: job postings (aggregators: LinkedIn Jobs, Indeed), news/press
    releases (news APIs/scraping), LinkedIn posts (public feed or Phantombuster/Proxycurl),
    company websites (monitoring for changes), funding announcements (Crunchbase/scraped),
    SEC filings (for larger companies)
  - Scan frequency: ~24-48 hours after triggering event (not real-time)
  - Matching is LLM-based: AI reads unstructured text and determines if it matches the
    plain-English signal definition. Essentially semantic classification
  Evidence: https://www.coldreach.ai/ feature descriptions, Product Hunt comments

  Signal verification / false positive prevention:
  - Shows SOURCE EVIDENCE alongside each signal (actual job posting text, LinkedIn post,
    news article) so user can verify
  - Relevance score displayed per signal (visible in demos, methodology not documented)
  - User feedback (thumbs up/down) improves matching over time
  - The plain-English definition allows more specificity than keyword matching, reducing
    false positives at the definition level
  - NO published false positive rate or confidence methodology
  Evidence: Product Hunt launch screenshots, demo videos

  The 3.8% reply rate claim — evidence assessment:
  - Claim appears at https://www.coldreach.ai/ — "Customers see 3.8% avg reply rates"
  - NO sample size, time period, methodology, or baseline comparison published
  - Industry average cold email reply rate: 1-3% (per Woodpecker.co, Lemlist benchmarks)
  - 3.8% is plausible but only modestly above average
  - Likely from aggregated early-adopter data (selection bias: early signal-tool adopters
    are probably already above-average at outreach)
  - NO independent verification found
  EVIDENCE STATUS: UNVERIFIED MARKETING CLAIM

  Outreach structuring:
  - For each triggered signal: research packet (signal event, company context, talking
    points) + draft email/LinkedIn message referencing the specific signal
  - Messages designed to be edited, not auto-sent. "Research + draft" not "automation"
  - Integrates with Outreach, Salesloft, Apollo for actual sending
  Evidence: https://www.coldreach.ai/features

  The "97M+ accounts" database:
  - Aggregation of public data: LinkedIn company profiles (~60M+), Crunchbase, government
    registrations, web-scraped company data
  - Company database, not contact database
  - For comparison: Apollo claims 60M+, ZoomInfo 100M+, LinkedIn has 60M+ company pages
  - Includes very small businesses and international companies where signal quality is lower
  - No documentation on data sourcing methodology
  Evidence: https://www.coldreach.ai/ (homepage claim)

  Pricing: ~$500-1,500/mo per G2 reviews
  Evidence: https://www.g2.com/products/coldreach/reviews

  KEY TAKEAWAY FOR OUR ARCHITECTURE:
  The plain-English signal definition is the pattern to steal. For Civ: "EPC contractor
  awarded a solar project over 100MW in ERCOT" as a monitoring query. The event-based
  approach (what companies DO, not what they read) maps directly to our ISO queue filings,
  permit applications, and contract awards. But our data sources are specialized (ISO
  queues, OSHA, SEC EDGAR) — more reliable than generic news scraping.

