  A4. Artisan — Personalization Waterfall
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  HIGH-LEVEL CONCEPT:
  Artisan's "Ava" AI SDR automates outreach by scraping data sources to find the best
  personalization angle per prospect, then generates and sends email/LinkedIn sequences.

  CRITICAL CORRECTION:
  The "4 layers" (signal/company/role/social proof) described earlier in this document
  are NOT documented in any Artisan public material. This framing likely came from a
  pitch deck or demo, not product documentation. What Artisan actually documents is
  a SELECTION algorithm — it picks the single best personalization angle, not layers.

  IMPLEMENTATION DETAIL:

  What Artisan actually documents:
  - Ava scrapes "dozens of integrated data sources" to find "the most relevant insights
    for each prospect"
  - System "analyze[s] and determine[s] the best form of personalization for each lead,
    weighing factors like relevance and timeliness"
  - This is a SELECTION algorithm (pick best angle), not a cascade (try A then B then C)
  Evidence: https://www.artisan.co/products/email-personalization, https://www.artisan.co/blog/ai-sdr

  Data sources:
  - Built-in database: 300M+ B2B contacts across 200 countries
  - CrunchBase (funding), BuiltWith (technographics), StoreLeads, Twitter/X, LinkedIn
    (via "Cyber Stalker" research tool), company websites, press releases, hiring data
  - Two internal tools:
    1. "Data Miner" — web scraper for demographics, technographics, buying intent, ICP fit
    2. "Cyber Stalker" — research assistant gathering prospect's digital footprint
  Evidence: https://www.artisan.co/ai-sales-agent

  Intent signal scoring:
  - First-party: pricing page visits (40-50 pts), resource downloads (30 pts), social/
    blog engagement (10-20 pts)
  - Third-party: funding, product updates, blog posts, social media, press, hiring
  - Custom CRM fields: "Intent Score", "Last High-Intent Action", "Topic Surge"
  - If-then triggers: "If views comparison guide + 200+ employees + uses HubSpot, enroll
    in high-fit automation workflow"
  Evidence: https://www.artisan.co/blog/intent-signals

  Fallback / degradation logic: NOT PUBLICLY DOCUMENTED
  - Industry best practice (not Artisan-specific):
    Tier 1 (high signal): 15-20 min deep research, full situational personalization
    Tier 2 (some signal): 5-8 min, 2-3 key points from LinkedIn/news
    Tier 3 (low/no signal): segment-level (industry + role + pain point) with one detail
  - Artisan's minimum viable personalization appears to be template with firmographic
    variables (company name, role, industry) — "Mad Libs with a logo" per one reviewer
  Evidence: https://www.saleshandy.com/blog/how-to-personalize-cold-emails/ (industry practice, not Artisan-specific)

  VERIFIED CASE STUDIES:
  - SaaStr: 6,892 emails, 3,574 new leads, 3.55% positive reply rate, 49.41% LinkedIn
    connection acceptance
  - Zirtual: 81,785 emails, 27,132 new leads, 3x higher replies than Apollo
  - Chain of Events: $700K ARR, 20x ROI ($28K annual spend), 6 months
  Evidence: https://www.artisan.co/casestudies

  COUNTERPOINT — independent reviews (100+ verified users):
  - "~1,400 emails sent. 0 responses received"
  - "Super poor quality emails... overpromising and underdelivering AI slop"
  - "Mad Libs with a logo"
  - Lead sourcing retrieved "3-7 C-level contacts from 3M+ records" (weak filtering)
  - Deliverability problems: DNS errors, broken warm-up timers
  - Early enthusiasm faded within 30-60 days for most users
  Evidence: https://coldreach.ai/blog/artisan-ai-review

  Is "personalization waterfall" an Artisan-specific term?
  NO — it is a mashup of two established patterns:
  1. Waterfall enrichment (cascading providers, predates Artisan — Clay, Lemlist use it,
     inspired by SiriusDecisions Demand Waterfall, 2002/2012, now Forrester)
  2. Tiered personalization (standard sales methodology — invest more research on
     higher-value prospects)
  Artisan branded the combination but didn't invent either concept.
  Evidence: https://www.saleshandy.com/blog/waterfall-enrichment/, https://www.lemlist.com/blog/waterfall-lead-enrichment

  Pricing: $2,400-$7,200/mo estimated (not published officially)
  Evidence: https://coldreach.ai/blog/best-ai-sdr-tool-2026

  KEY TAKEAWAY FOR OUR ARCHITECTURE:
  The 4-layer personalization framework (signal/company/role/social proof) is a useful
  DESIGN PATTERN even though Artisan doesn't implement it well. We should build the
  framework ourselves as a structured research packet. The honest takeaway: AI SDR
  quality varies wildly. The research packet matters more than the email generation.
  Invest in research depth, let humans (or a good LLM) write the outreach.

