  A5. Perplexity — Multi-Source Verification Architecture
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  HIGH-LEVEL CONCEPT:
  Perplexity is a search engine with a real retrieval pipeline (not just an LLM with
  web access). It has a custom index (200B+ URLs on Vespa AI), a three-layer reranking
  system with an ML quality gate, a custom inference engine (ROSE), and a Model Council
  feature that runs queries through 3 frontier models with a 4th synthesizer.

  IMPLEMENTATION DETAIL:

  Model Council (launched February 5, 2026):
  - Available to Max and Enterprise Max subscribers
  - Runs query through 3 frontier models SIMULTANEOUSLY:
    GPT-5.4, Claude Opus 4.6, Gemini 3.1 Pro (models updated over time)
  - User selects which 3 models to use
  - A 4th "chair" model (defaults to Claude Opus 4.5, user-configurable) SYNTHESIZES
  Evidence: https://www.perplexity.ai/hub/blog/introducing-model-council, https://www.perplexity.ai/help-center/en/articles/13641704

  How the council works (NOT a simple vote):
  - All 3 models produce independent responses in parallel
  - Chair model inspects all outputs
  - Identifies consensus sentences (areas of agreement)
  - Tags unique/novel points from individual models
  - EXPLICITLY FLAGS disagreements rather than silently picking one
  - UI: color cues mark agreement zones, warning icons mark conflicts
  - Example: if GPT says X and Claude contradicts X, the synthesizer shows both with
    the conflict highlighted
  Evidence: https://www.humai.blog/perplexitys-model-council-queries-gpt-claude-and-gemini-at-once/, https://auto-post.io/blog/perplexity-launches-model-council

  WHAT IS NOT DOCUMENTED:
  - Exact prompt template for the synthesizer
  - Whether chair model accesses raw source citations from each council member or just text
  - Weighting algorithm (if any) for which model's output takes priority

  Source selection — the 5-stage RAG pipeline:
  1. Query Intent Parsing — LLM-based semantic understanding (not keyword matching)
  2. Live Web Retrieval — dispatches to real-time search index (Google + Bing indexes)
  3. Snippet Extraction — documents chunked into segments, specific paragraphs returned
  4. Synthesized Answer — model cannot output anything unsourced, inline citations required
  5. Conversational Refinement — maintains context for follow-ups
  Evidence: https://blog.bytebytego.com/p/how-perplexity-built-an-ai-google

  Three-layer reranking (L1/L2/L3) — reverse-engineered from third-party analysis:

  L1 (Initial Retrieval):
  - Hybrid retrieval: dense (vector embeddings) + sparse (BM25 lexical matching)
  - Optimized for speed. Produces candidate set

  L2 (Standard Ranking):
  - Conventional authority and relevance signals
  - Cross-encoder reranker models
  - Produces ordered list

  L3 (XGBoost Quality Gate) — the critical filter:
  - Specifically targets entity searches (company names, people, products)
  - Parameters include:
    - l3_reranker_drop_threshold — quality minimum a source must clear
    - l3_reranker_drop_all_docs_if_count_less_equal — drops entire result set if too
      few sources pass quality bar
  - Uses BERT-based entity linking for disambiguation
  - Sources that are vague, promotional, or fail entity disambiguation get lower scores
  Evidence: https://ipullrank.com/ai-search-manual/search-architecture (reverse-engineered)

  ML ranking signals (59 identified factors):
  - Lexical relevance, vector similarity
  - Domain authority (composite feature in ML model, not standalone PageRank-like score)
  - Document freshness (heavy bias toward recent "Last Modified" dates)
  - User engagement signals
  - Entity clarity and contextual linking (pages where entities clearly named get preference)
  - AI-generated content detection (internal algorithms, acknowledged as imperfect)
  Evidence: https://authoritytech.io/blog/how-perplexity-selects-sources-algorithm-2026, https://metehan.ai/blog/perplexity-ai-seo-59-ranking-patterns/

  Source authority scoring:
  - Domain authority (composite feature, not a single number)
  - Semantic relevance to query
  - Presence of direct, verifiable facts
  - Recent Last Modified dates (heavily weighted)
  - Entity prominence — entities clearly named and contextually linked
  - NO publicly documented PageRank-like standalone score
  Evidence: https://www.datastudios.org/post/perplexity-ai-models-explained, https://www.xfunnel.ai/blog/inside-perplexity-ai

  Citation verification — honest assessment:
  - Sonar models fine-tuned to prefer evidence-grounded answers
  - Architecture enforces "nothing output unless sourced"
  - Sonar cites 2-3x more sources than comparable Gemini models
  - BUT: Tow Center study (200 tests, 8 AI search engines): Perplexity had LOWEST failure
    rate but still incorrect 37% of the time
  - Known to cite AI-generated spam from sketchy blogs and LinkedIn posts
  - No NLI (Natural Language Inference) verification step publicly documented — grounding
    appears enforced at TRAINING TIME, not inference-time post-hoc verification
  - This is a genuine gap in what is publicly known
  Evidence: https://www.niemanlab.org/2025/03/ai-search-engines-fail-to-produce-accurate-citations/, https://futurism.com/the-byte/perplexity-citing-ai-generated-spam, https://www.perplexity.ai/hub/blog/meet-new-sonar

  Conflict resolution:
  - Deep Research: conflicting claims flagged and double-checked. Model splits query into
    subtopics, searches each independently, writes structured notes, surfaces conflicts
  - Model Council: synthesizer flags disagreements with warning icons/color cues
  - Standard search: weighted consensus with confidence scores (e.g., "85% agreement on
    2C threshold impacts")
  - Synthesis errors REMAIN COMMON: conditional claims presented as definitive, conflicting
    reports merged without explicit qualification
  Evidence: https://www.datastudios.org/post/perplexity-ai-accuracy-and-reliability, https://www.usaii.org/ai-insights/what-is-perplexity-deep-research

  Pro Search (multi-step):
  1. Agent creates step-by-step plan (planning separated from execution)
  2. Per step: generates and executes specific search queries
  3. Sequential: step N results passed as context to step N+1
  4. Each step: focused retrieval → rank sources → synthesize intermediate summary
  5. Supports tool use: code interpreter, Wolfram Alpha
  Evidence: https://www.langchain.com/breakoutagents/perplexity

  Deep Research (comprehensive reports):
  - 20-50 targeted queries per research task
  - Reads hundreds of sources (200+ per report)
  - Process: split into subtopics → dedicated search per subtopic → partial answers as
    structured notes → conflicting claims flagged → single narrative with citations
  - Output: 5-15 page reports, 2-4 minutes completion
  Evidence: https://www.perplexity.ai/hub/blog/introducing-perplexity-deep-research

  ROSE inference engine:
  - Python + PyTorch for model definitions, critical hot paths in Rust
  - Speculative decoding: draft model generates n candidate tokens, target model scores,
    longest sequence above threshold accepted, target provides n+1th token "free"
  - Model routing: small classifier determines query complexity, routes to smallest
    adequate model
  - In-house Sonar family (fine-tuned from Llama 3 70B) + third-party via Amazon Bedrock
  - Infrastructure: AWS, NVIDIA H100 GPUs, Kubernetes, TensorRT-LLM
  Evidence: https://www.perplexity.ai/hub/blog/accelerating-sonar-through-speculation, https://blog.bytebytego.com/p/how-perplexity-built-an-ai-google

  KEY TAKEAWAY FOR OUR ARCHITECTURE:
  Three patterns to steal: (1) The L3 quality gate with entity disambiguation — our
  "is this the EPC?" problem IS an entity disambiguation problem. (2) The Model Council's
  explicit conflict flagging — instead of picking one answer, show competing claims with
  scores. (3) Deep Research's subtopic decomposition — our EPC research should decompose
  into structured sub-questions (who filed the project? who won the EPC contract? what's
  their construction timeline? do OSHA records corroborate?).

  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  A6. Fellegi-Sunter Model — Entity Resolution
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  Three-zone thresholding for entity matching:
  - Above upper threshold (>90%): auto-merge (same entity)
  - Below lower threshold (<50%): auto-reject (different entities)
  - Between thresholds (50-90%): manual review queue (uncertain)

  Field-level comparison weights:
  - Rare value matches get HIGH weight (matching on unusual company name = strong evidence)
  - Common value matches get LOW weight (matching on "LLC" or "Inc" = weak evidence)
  - Composite score = sum of all field-level weights

  Key insight: Systems that force binary yes/no on ambiguous data either miss matches or
  create false merges. The "uncertain" zone with human review catches the hard cases.

  Source: O'Reilly Hands-On Entity Resolution ch04

